project.name: Unified metadata schema
project.desc: The unified semantic metadata schema to power reuse of NGS data in research and healthcare.
project.author: David C. Ruvolo
K. Joeri van der Velde
Morris A. Swertz

dataset.name: Unified metadata schema
dataset.desc: The unified semantic metadata schema to power reuse of NGS data in research and healthcare.

concept.name: Data releases
concept.desc: The act of making data or other structured information accessible to the public or to the user group of a database.

concept.name: id
concept.desc: One or more characters used to identify, name, or characterize the nature, properties, or contents of a thing.

concept.name: name
concept.desc: The words or language units by which a thing is known.

concept.name: Studies
concept.desc: A detailed examination, analysis, or critical inspection of one or multiple subjects designed to discover facts.

concept.name: Acronym
concept.desc: The non-unique initials or abbreviated name used for identification.

concept.name: Completion date
concept.desc: The date on which the concluding information for this study is completed. Usually, this is when the last subject has a final visit, or the main analysis has finished, or any other protocol-defined completion date.

concept.name: Contact email
concept.desc: An email address for the purpose of contacting the study contact person.

concept.name: Contact person
concept.desc: Name of study contact.

concept.name: Current study status
concept.desc: The status of a study or trial.

concept.name: Description
concept.desc: A statement or piece of writing that provides details on this study.

concept.name: Identifier
concept.desc: A unique proper name or character sequence that identifies this particular study.

concept.name: Inclusion criteria
concept.desc: The conditions which, if met, make an person eligible for participation in this study.

concept.name: Name
concept.desc: A name that designates this study.

concept.name: Number of subjects enrolled
concept.desc: An integer specifying the quantity of study subjects enrolled in the study at the current time.

concept.name: Numer of samples collected
concept.desc: An integer specifying the quantity of samples collected at the current time.

concept.name: Principal investigator
concept.desc: An investigator who is responsible for all aspects of the conduct of a study.

concept.name: Start date
concept.desc: The date on which this study began.

concept.name: Study design
concept.desc: A plan specification comprised of protocols (which may specify how and what kinds of data will be gathered) that are executed as part of this study.

concept.name: belongsToDataRelease
concept.desc: The act of making data or other structured information accessible to the public or to the user group of a database.

concept.name: Subjects
concept.desc: Persons who are observed, analyzed, examined, investigated, experimented upon, or/and treated in the course of a particular study.

concept.name: Affiliated institute contact email
concept.desc: Email address of the contact person or organization

concept.name: Affiliated institute contact person
concept.desc: A person acting as a channel for communication between groups or on behalf of a group.

concept.name: Age at death
concept.desc: The age at which death occurred.

concept.name: Alternative identifiers
concept.desc: A backup sequence of characters used to identify an entity.

concept.name: Ancestry
concept.desc: Population category defined using ancestry informative markers (AIMs) based on genetic/genomic data.

concept.name: Belongs to data release
concept.desc: The act of making data or other structured information accessible to the public or to the user group of a database.

concept.name: Belongs to family
concept.desc: A domestic group, or a number of domestic groups linked through descent (demonstrated or stipulated) from a common ancestor, marriage, or adoption.

concept.name: Belongs to father
concept.desc: Having to do with the father, coming from the father, or related through the father.

concept.name: Belongs to mother
concept.desc: A designation that has some relationship to motherhood.

concept.name: Belongs to study
concept.desc: Reference to the study or studies in which this person participates.

concept.name: Belongs with family members
concept.desc: Any individual related biologically or legally to another individual.

concept.name: Belongs with twin
concept.desc: Either of two offspring born from the same pregnancy.

concept.name: Consanguinity
concept.desc: Genetic relatedness between individuals who are descendants of at least one common ancestor.

concept.name: Country of birth
concept.desc: The country that this person was born in.

concept.name: Country of residence
concept.desc: Country of residence at enrollment.

concept.name: Date of birth
concept.desc: The calendar date on which a person was born.

concept.name: Date of death
concept.desc: The calendar date of subject's death.

concept.name: Fetal status
concept.desc: Any tissue from a fetus.

concept.name: First visit date
concept.desc: The date for the first patient visit.

concept.name: Gender at birth
concept.desc: Assigned gender is one's gender which was assigned at birth, typically by a medical and/or legal organization, and then later registered with other organizations. Such a designation is typically based off of the superficial appearance of external genitalia present at birth.

concept.name: Gender identity
concept.desc: A person's concept of self as being male and masculine or female and feminine, or ambivalent, based in part on physical characteristics, parental responses, and psychological and social pressures. It is the internal experience of gender role. For practical reasons the lookups are limited to first and second-level entries, but can be expanded when needed. Note that 'Gender at birth', 'Genotypic sex' and any (gender-related) hormone therapies in 'Medication' are usually medically more relevant than this term.

concept.name: Genotypic sex
concept.desc: A biological sex quality inhering in an individual based upon genotypic composition of sex chromosomes.

concept.name: Inclusion status
concept.desc: A findings domain that contains general subject characteristics that are evaluated periodically to determine if they have changed.

concept.name: Participates in study
concept.desc: Reference to the study or studies in which this person participates.

concept.name: Primary affiliated institute
concept.desc: The most significant institute for medical consultation and/or study inclusion in context of the genetic disease of this person.

concept.name: Resources in other institutes
concept.desc: Material or data related to this person that is not captured by this system though known to be available in other institutes such as biobanks or hospitals.

concept.name: Year of birth
concept.desc: The year in which this person was born.

concept.name: Year of death
concept.desc: The year in which an individual derived.

valueSet.name: Inclusioncriteria_Opts
valueSet.desc: Options for The conditions which, if met, make an person eligible for participation in this study.

designation.displayName: An inclusion criterion that defines and states a Body Mass Index range, which if met, makes an individual suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion that defines and states an age bracket which, if met, makes an entity suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.

An inclusion criterion that uses the age of majority for a state or institution, where one is generally considered to be an adult, which if met, makes an individual suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.

An inclusion criterion that defines and states one or more clinically relevant histories of exposure of an entity, which, if met, makes the entity suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.

An inclusion criterion that defines and states one or more clinically relevant planned processes that a human being actively participates in , which, if met, makes the human being suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion that defines and states one or more countries of residence which, if met, makes a human being suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion that is based on fitting within the defined characteristics of a population based study design.
An inclusion criteria that defines and states one or more ethnicities which, if met, makes an entity suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion that defines and states one or more family statuses, which, if met, makes a human being suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion that defines and states one or more gravidity statuses of an organism, which, if met, makes the entity suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.

An inclusion criterion that defines and states one or more clinically significant bodily components, dispositions, and/or bodily processes of an entity that are inferred from relevant clinical findings or self-reported, which, if met, makes the entity suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion defines that a human being has to be a hospital patient to be suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion that defines and states one or more sexes which, if met, makes an entity suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.
An inclusion criterion that defines and states a a set of medications, which, if used by an entity, makes that entity suitable for a given task or participation in a given process.

valueSet.name: Currentstudystatus_Opts
valueSet.desc: Options for The status of a study or trial.

designation.displayName: A clinical study status designating the study open to accrual.
Protocol is approved by the review board.

concept.displayName: Blinded Status at SDTM Dataset Generation

designation.displayName: The blinding status of the trial at the point in time when the SDTM datasets are generated.
An interruption in some or all clinical trial activities.
An interruption in clinical trial activity by the sponsor that is not in the clinical protocol with an intention to resume the study.
An indication that a study is able to add subjects.

A business process status of a clinical study that refers to the study that started the execution of activities specified by the study protocol. The data associated with the performed study describes quantitatively and qualitatively actual observations and events occurring in the study after its approval such as actual accrual numbers dates of subject enrollment etc.

A business process status of a clinical study which occurs before the study starts. A study plan on which the clinical trial is based focuses on several priority parameters that include but are not limited to the types of subjects eligible to participate in the study targeted accrual numbers schedules and durations of interventions the length of the study and the planned duration of a subject participation. These outlines are a part of a study protocol which is more a detailed and comprehensive study document.
A clinical study protocol status designating the protocol that has been withdrawn prior to the complete review.
A clinical study protocol review status designating the protocol that was deferred pending additional information or/and action(s).
A clinical study protocol review status designating the protocol that was denied the approval.
A clinical study status designating the study that stopped patient accrual; other study activities specified by the study protocol might continue.

concept.displayName: Study Closed to Accrual and Treatment

designation.displayName: A clinical study status designating the study that stopped further patient accrual as well as the treatment of the subjects already enrolled in the trial.
A clinical study status designating the study has been completed normally according to the protocol. Subject enrollment stopped. No participants are treated or being followed up.
Refers to the closing of a study to further enrollment.

A clinical study status designating that an order has been issued to a study sponsor to delay a proposed investigation or to suspend an ongoing one. When a proposed study is placed on clinical hold subjects may not be given the investigational product as part of the study. When an ongoing study is placed on clinical hold no new subjects may be recruited to the study and placed on the investigational product. Subjects already in the study have to stop receiving therapy involving the investigational agent unless the FDA specifically permits it.
A clinical study status designating the study has been stopped prematurely and will not resume. Subject enrollment stopped. No participants are treated or being followed up.
A clinical study status designating the study that has been stopped prematurely: Subject enrollment never started. Study will not resume.
The discontinuation of a clinical trial prior to the planned end date.

designation.displayName: A gender identity in question or in the process of being questioned.

An indication that no gender identity has developed. Use for neonates whose assigned sex at birth is 'undifferentiated'. For a person who identifies as not having a gender, use 'non-gendered identity'.
Having an identity considered nonbinary or as falling under the nonbinary umbrella.
A gender which has a certain prerequisite which may be unrelated to gender, such as one belonging to a particular culture or indigenous group.

Any of various gender identities defined by their inability to be described, communicated, or otherwise understood.
Having a multiple gender identities simultaneously.
Having a gender identity that is genderless or having no gender identity whatsoever.
Having a gender identity which overlaps somewhat with other gender identities but not in their entirety.
Having a gender identity which includes part of another gender identity, but not all of it (for example, identifying somewhat with female, but not entirely).
A datum representing a person's gender identity which is not listed.
A datum representing that a person's gender identity is not known for any of various reasons.
A datum representing when an individual does not wish to disclose their gender identity, thereby making their gender identity unknown.

valueSet.name: Genderatbirth_Opts
valueSet.desc: Options for Assigned gender is one's gender which was assigned at birth, typically by a medical and/or legal organization, and then later registered with other organizations. Such a designation is typically based off of the superficial appearance of external genitalia present at birth.

designation.displayName: An assignment of an 'U' gender shortly after birth. Note that 'U' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.
An assignment of an 'X' gender shortly after birth. Note that 'X' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.

An assignment of a diverse gender marker shortly after birth. Note that 'diverse' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that 'diverse' itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context.

An assignment of a 'eunuch' gender marker shortly after birth. Note that 'eunuch' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that 'eunuch' itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context. This term may also be offensive depending on the context.
An assignment of a female gender shortly after birth.

An assignment of an indeterminate gender marker shortly after birth. Note that 'indeterminate' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that 'indeterminate' itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context.

An assignment of an intersex gender marker shortly after birth. Note that 'intersex' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that 'intersex' itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context.
An assignment of a male gender shortly after birth.
Use in situations where no gender was assigned at birth, i.e. no birth certificate was issued shortly after birth or no birth certificate gender was recorded.
An assignment of a nonbinary gender shortly after birth. Note that 'nonbinary' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.
An assignment of an 'other' gender marker shortly after birth. Note that 'other' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.

An assignment of a 'third gender' gender marker shortly after birth. Note that 'third gender' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that 'third gender' itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context. This term may also be offensive depending on the context.
An assignment of an 'unspecified' gender shortly after birth. Note that 'unspecified' is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.

valueSet.name: Genotypicsex_Opts
valueSet.desc: Options for A biological sex quality inhering in an individual based upon genotypic composition of sex chromosomes.

designation.displayName: The normal genotype of a female human.
The normal genotype of a male human.

An abnormal sex chromosome karyotype where the individual is missing either a second X chromosome or the Y chromosome. The normal autosomal karyotype is present. This karyotype is associated with Turner Syndrome.
An abnormal sex chromosome karyotype where the individual is missing a second X chromosome and has some chromosomal material from the Y chromosome. The normal autosomal karyotype is present.
An abnormal sex chromosome karyotype where the individual has three copies of the X chromosome. The normal autosomal karyotype is present. This karyotype is associated with triple X syndrome.

An abnormal sex chromosome karyotype where the individual has two copies of the X chromosome and one copy of the Y chromosome. The normal autosomal karyotype is present. This karyotype is associated with Klinefelter syndrome.
An abnormal sex chromosome karyotype where the individual has one X chromosome and has two copies of the Y chromosome. The normal autosomal karyotype is present.
An abnormal sex chromosome karyotype where the individual has four copies of the X chromosome. The normal autosomal karyotype is present.
An abnormal sex chromosome karyotype where the individual has three copies of the X chromosome and one copy of the Y chromosome. The normal autosomal karyotype is present.
A rare sex chromosome abnormality in which a male child has an extra X and Y chromosome.
A rare sex chromosome abnormality in which a female child has 3 extra X chromosomes.

Rare syndrome caused by chromosomal defects and characterized by the presence of multiple X chromosomes and one Y chromosome. Signs and symptoms include short stature, mental retardation, hypogonadism, undescended testes, gynecomastia, and hypotonia.
